{
  "If a force F(x) acts on an object as it moves from x = a to x = b, the work done is:": "",
  "F(a) * (b - a)": "",
  "F(b) - F(a)": "",
  "d/dx [F(x)] evaluated at b": "",
  "integral from a to b of F(x) dx": "",
  "Work done by a variable force F(x) over a displacement from x = a to x = b is W = integral from a to b of F(x) dx. This generalizes the constant-force formula W = F * d to variable forces.": "",
  "A spring has natural length 10 cm and requires a force of 6 N to stretch it 2 cm beyond its natural length. How much work is done stretching it from natural length to 4 cm beyond?": "",
  "12 N*cm": "",
  "6 N*cm": "",
  "24 N*cm": "",
  "48 N*cm": "",
  "By Hooke's Law, F = kx where k = 6/2 = 3 N/cm. Work = integral from 0 to 4 of 3x dx = (3/2)x^2 from 0 to 4 = (3/2)(16) = 24 N*cm.": "",
  "The velocity of a particle is v(t) = 3t^2 - 6t m/s. The total distance traveled from t = 0 to t = 4 is found by:": "",
  "|integral from 0 to 4 of (3t^2 - 6t) dt|": "",
  "integral from 0 to 4 of (3t^2 - 6t) dt": "",
  "integral from 0 to 4 of |3t^2 - 6t| dt": "",
  "integral from 0 to 4 of (3t^2 - 6t)^2 dt": "",
  "Total distance traveled requires integrating the absolute value of velocity: integral of |v(t)| dt. This accounts for direction changes. Plain integration of v(t) gives net displacement, not total distance.": "",
  "Hooke's Law states that the force needed to stretch or compress a spring by x units from its natural length is:": "",
  "F = kx": "",
  "F = kx^2": "",
  "F = k*sqrt(x)": "",
  "F = k/x": "",
  "Hooke's Law states F = kx, where k is the spring constant and x is the displacement from the spring's natural (equilibrium) length. The force is directly proportional to the displacement.": "",
  "The kinetic energy of an object with mass m and velocity v is:": "",
  "mv": "",
  "(1/2)mv^2": "",
  "m^2*v/2": "",
  "mv^2": "",
  "Kinetic energy is KE = (1/2)mv^2. This can be derived from the work-energy theorem: the work done on an object equals the change in its kinetic energy.": "",
  "A force of F(x) = 10/(x^2) Newtons acts on an object. How much work is done moving the object from x = 1 to x = 5 meters?": "",
  "10 J": "",
  "50 J": "",
  "2 J": "",
  "8 J": "",
  "W = integral from 1 to 5 of 10/x^2 dx = 10 * [-1/x] from 1 to 5 = 10(-1/5 + 1) = 10(4/5) = 8 J.": "",
  "The position of a particle is s(t) = t^3 - 3t^2 + 2t. The displacement from t = 0 to t = 3 is:": "",
  "3": "",
  "6": "",
  "12": "",
  "0": "",
  "Displacement = s(3) - s(0) = (27 - 27 + 6) - (0) = 6. Alternatively, displacement = integral from 0 to 3 of v(t) dt = integral of (3t^2 - 6t + 2) dt = [t^3 - 3t^2 + 2t] from 0 to 3 = 6.": "",
  "The work done in pumping water out of the top of a tank is computed by integrating which quantity?": "",
  "Mass times acceleration, especially during periods of significant change": "",
  "Pressure times area, at least according to standard theory": "",
  "Weight density times cross-sectional area times the distance each layer must be lifted": "",
  "Volume times height, at least according to standard theory": "",
  "To pump water from a tank, we slice the water into thin horizontal layers. Each layer has a weight (density * g * A(y) * dy) and must be lifted a certain distance. The total work integrates weight-density * A(y) * (lift distance) * dy over the depth of the water.": "",
  "A 5 kg object moves with velocity v(t) = 4t m/s. The net work done on the object from t = 0 to t = 3 is:": "",
  "90 J": "",
  "720 J": "",
  "360 J": "",
  "180 J": "",
  "By the work-energy theorem, W = change in KE = (1/2)mv(3)^2 - (1/2)mv(0)^2 = (1/2)(5)(12)^2 - 0 = (1/2)(5)(144) = 360 J.": "",
  "The gravitational force on an object of mass m at distance r from Earth's center is F = GMm/r^2. The work done moving the object from r = R to r = 2R is:": "",
  "GMm/R": "",
  "2GMm/R": "",
  "GMm/(4R)": "",
  "GMm/(2R)": "",
  "W = integral from R to 2R of GMm/r^2 dr = GMm[-1/r] from R to 2R = GMm(-1/(2R) + 1/R) = GMm(1/(2R)) = GMm/(2R).": "",
  "What is the work-energy theorem?": "",
  "Work equals force divided by distance": "",
  "Energy is always conserved in a closed system": "",
  "The net work done on an object equals the change in its kinetic energy": "",
  "The total work done equals the object's potential energy": "",
  "The work-energy theorem states that the net work done on an object equals the change in its kinetic energy: W_net = (1/2)mv_f^2 - (1/2)mv_i^2. This connects the integral of force over distance to the object's motion.": "",
  "What does 'net displacement' mean in kinematics?": "",
  "The maximum distance from the starting point": "",
  "The change in position from start to finish, accounting for direction": "",
  "The total distance traveled regardless of direction": "",
  "The average speed over a time interval": "",
  "Net displacement is the change in position from the starting point to the ending point, accounting for direction. It is found by integrating velocity (not speed) over the time interval: integral of v(t) dt.": "",
  "What is the spring constant in Hooke's Law?": "",
  "The natural length of the spring": "",
  "The maximum force the spring can exert": "",
  "The mass attached to the spring": "",
  "A proportionality constant that measures the stiffness of the spring": "",
  "The spring constant k measures the stiffness of the spring. A larger k means the spring is stiffer and requires more force to stretch or compress by the same amount. Its units are force per length (e.g., N/m).": "",
  "What does 'variable force' mean in the context of work calculations?": "",
  "A force that only acts for a limited time": "",
  "A force that cannot be measured": "",
  "A force whose magnitude changes depending on position or time": "",
  "A force that acts in multiple directions simultaneously": "",
  "A variable force is one whose magnitude (and possibly direction) changes as a function of position or time. Integration is needed to compute work done by a variable force, since the simple formula W = Fd only applies to constant forces.": "",
  "What is potential energy in the context of physics applications of integration?": "",
  "Energy stored due to an object's position or configuration": "",
  "The total energy in a closed system": "",
  "The rate at which work is done": "",
  "Energy due to motion": "",
  "Potential energy is energy stored in an object due to its position or configuration. For example, gravitational PE = mgh and elastic PE = (1/2)kx^2. The work done against a conservative force equals the gain in potential energy.": "",
  "What is the unit of work in the SI system?": "",
  "Watt": "",
  "Newton": "",
  "Pascal": "",
  "Joule": "",
  "The SI unit of work is the joule (J). One joule equals one newton-meter (N*m), which is the work done when a force of one newton moves an object one meter in the direction of the force.": "",
  "What does 'impulse' mean in physics?": "",
  "The rate of change of energy": "",
  "The product of mass and acceleration": "",
  "The integral of force with respect to time, equal to the change in momentum": "",
  "The instantaneous velocity of an object": "",
  "Impulse is the integral of force with respect to time: J = integral of F(t) dt. By Newton's second law, impulse equals the change in momentum: J = mv_f - mv_i. This is the impulse-momentum theorem.": "",
  "What is the difference between 'work' and 'power' in physics?": "",
  "Work requires constant force, power requires variable force": "",
  "Work is the total energy transferred, while power is the rate at which work is done": "",
  "Power is always larger than work": "",
  "They are the same quantity measured in different units": "",
  "Work measures the total energy transferred by a force over a distance (W = integral of F dx, measured in joules). Power is the rate at which work is done (P = dW/dt, measured in watts). Power tells you how quickly energy is being transferred.": "",
  "What does 'weight density' mean in fluid problems?": "",
  "Weight (force due to gravity) per unit volume": "",
  "Total weight of the fluid": "",
  "Pressure per unit area": "",
  "Mass per unit volume": "",
  "Weight density (often denoted rho*g or just w) is the weight per unit volume of a fluid. For water, it is approximately 62.4 lb/ft^3 or 9800 N/m^3. It equals mass density times gravitational acceleration.": "",
  "What does the term 'conservative force' mean?": "",
  "A force that does no work": "",
  "A force that conserves velocity": "",
  "A force that always decreases over time": "",
  "A force where the work done depends only on start and end positions, not the path taken": "",
  "A conservative force is one for which the work done depends only on the initial and final positions, not on the path taken between them. Gravity and spring forces are conservative; friction is not. Conservative forces have associated potential energy functions.": "",
  "A 50-meter chain weighing 2 kg/m hangs from the top of a building. How much work is required to pull the entire chain to the top?": "",
  "49,000 J": "",
  "12,250 J": "",
  "9,800 J": "",
  "24,500 J": "",
  "Consider a small segment at distance y below the top. It weighs 2*9.8 dy = 19.6 dy N and must be lifted y meters. Work = integral from 0 to 50 of 19.6*y dy = 19.6 * [y^2/2] from 0 to 50 = 19.6 * 1250 = 24,500 J.": "",
  "A rocket burns fuel at a rate that decreases its mass. If the thrust force is a constant 5000 N and the rocket moves from x = 0 to x = 100 m in a straight line, what is the work done by the thrust?": "",
  "250,000 J": "",
  "5,000,000 J": "",
  "500,000 J": "",
  "50,000 J": "",
  "Since the thrust force is constant at 5000 N, W = integral from 0 to 100 of 5000 dx = 5000 * 100 = 500,000 J. The changing mass affects acceleration but not the work calculation when force is given directly.": "",
  "A car accelerates from rest with velocity v(t) = 3t^2 m/s. What is the total distance traveled in the first 4 seconds?": "",
  "64 m": "",
  "96 m": "",
  "48 m": "",
  "32 m": "",
  "Since v(t) = 3t^2 >= 0 for all t >= 0, total distance = integral from 0 to 4 of 3t^2 dt = [t^3] from 0 to 4 = 64 m. Because velocity is always non-negative, distance equals displacement.": "",
  "A cylindrical tank of radius 3 m and height 8 m is full of water (density 1000 kg/m^3). How much work is required to pump all the water over the top edge?": "",
  "9800*9*pi*8 J": "",
  "9800*3*pi*32 J": "",
  "9800*9*pi*32 J": "",
  "9800*9*pi*64 J": "",
  "Place the origin at the bottom. A thin layer at height y has volume pi*3^2*dy = 9*pi dy and weight 9800*9*pi dy. It must be lifted (8 - y) meters. W = integral from 0 to 8 of 9800*9*pi*(8 - y) dy = 9800*9*pi * [8y - y^2/2] from 0 to 8 = 9800*9*pi*(64 - 32) = 9800*9*pi*32 J.": "",
  "A spring requires 10 J of work to stretch it from its natural length to 0.5 m beyond its natural length. How much additional work is needed to stretch it an additional 0.5 m (from 0.5 m to 1.0 m beyond natural length)?": "",
  "20 J": "",
  "30 J": "",
  "40 J": "",
  "From W = (1/2)kx^2, we get 10 = (1/2)k(0.5)^2, so k = 80 N/m. Work from 0.5 to 1.0 = (1/2)(80)(1)^2 - (1/2)(80)(0.5)^2 = 40 - 10 = 30 J. The additional work is greater because the force increases with displacement.": "",
  "A bucket weighing 5 kg is lifted at a constant rate from the bottom of a 30-meter well. The bucket leaks sand at a rate of 0.1 kg/m. How much work is done lifting the bucket to the top?": "",
  "882 J": "",
  "1029 J": "",
  "1470 J": "",
  "1323 J": "",
  "At height y meters, the bucket's mass is (5 - 0.1y) kg. The force is (5 - 0.1y)*9.8 N. Work = integral from 0 to 30 of 9.8(5 - 0.1y) dy = 9.8[5y - 0.05y^2] from 0 to 30 = 9.8(150 - 45) = 9.8 * 105 = 1029 J.": "",
  "A ball is thrown upward with initial velocity 20 m/s. Ignoring air resistance, its velocity is v(t) = 20 - 9.8t m/s. What is the maximum height reached?": "",
  "Approximately 10.2 m": "",
  "Approximately 30.6 m": "",
  "Approximately 20.4 m": "",
  "Approximately 40.8 m": "",
  "The ball reaches max height when v(t) = 0, giving t = 20/9.8 approximately 2.04 s. Height = integral from 0 to 20/9.8 of (20 - 9.8t) dt = [20t - 4.9t^2] from 0 to 2.04 = 20(2.04) - 4.9(2.04)^2 = 40.8 - 20.4 = 20.4 m.": "",
  "A conical tank (vertex down) has a radius of 4 m at the top and a height of 10 m. It is filled with oil of density 800 kg/m^3. How much work is needed to pump all the oil over the top?": "",
  "800*9.8*pi*(16/100) * integral from 0 to 10 of y^2*(10-y) dy": "",
  "800*9.8*pi*4 * integral from 0 to 10 of y*(10-y) dy": "",
  "800*9.8*pi * integral from 0 to 10 of y^3 dy": "",
  "800*9.8*pi*16 * integral from 0 to 10 of (10-y) dy": "",
  "With origin at the vertex, at height y the radius is r = (4/10)y = 2y/5. The cross-sectional area is pi*(2y/5)^2 = 4*pi*y^2/25. A layer at height y weighs 800*9.8*(4*pi*y^2/25) dy and must be lifted (10 - y). So W = 800*9.8*pi*(4/25) * integral from 0 to 10 of y^2*(10 - y) dy, which equals 800*9.8*pi*(16/100) * integral from 0 to 10 of y^2*(10-y) dy.": "",
  "A particle moves along the x-axis with velocity v(t) = sin(pi*t) m/s. What is the total distance traveled from t = 0 to t = 2?": "",
  "0 m": "",
  "2 m": "",
  "2/pi m": "",
  "4/pi m": "",
  "v(t) = sin(pi*t) is positive on (0,1) and negative on (1,2). Total distance = integral from 0 to 1 of sin(pi*t) dt + integral from 1 to 2 of |sin(pi*t)| dt = [-cos(pi*t)/pi] from 0 to 1 + [cos(pi*t)/pi] from 1 to 2 = (1/pi + 1/pi) + (1/pi + 1/pi) = 4/pi m.": "",
  "An elevator cable weighs 8 N/m and supports a 1000 N elevator car. If the cable is 50 m long when the car is at the bottom, how much work is done lifting the car 50 m to the top?": "",
  "80,000 J": "",
  "60,000 J": "",
  "70,000 J": "",
  "Work to lift the car = 1000 * 50 = 50,000 J. Work to lift the cable: when the car is y meters up, the hanging cable is (50 - y) meters long, weighing 8(50 - y) N. Cable work = integral from 0 to 50 of 8(50 - y) dy = 8[50y - y^2/2] from 0 to 50 = 8(2500 - 1250) = 10,000 J. Total = 50,000 + 10,000 = 60,000 J.": ""
}